Fitbit_Analysis

Rita Munoz

11/1/2022

Case Scenario

You are a junior data analyst working on the marketing analyst team at Bellabeat, a high-tech manufacturer of health-focused products for women. Bellabeat is a successful small company, but they have the potential to become a larger player in the global smart device market. Urška Sršen, cofounder and Chief Creative Officer of Bellabeat, believes that analyzing smart device fitness data could help unlock new growth opportunities for the company. You have been asked to focus on one of Bellabeat’s products and analyze smart device data to gain insight into how consumers are using their smart devices. The insights you discover will then help guide marketing strategy for the company. You will present your analysis to the Bellabeat executive team along with your high-level recommendations for Bellabeat’s marketing strategy.

Characters and Products

  • Characters
    • Urška Sršen: Bellabeat’s cofounder and Chief Creative Officer
    • Sando Mur: Mathematician and Bellabeat’s cofounder; key member of the Bellabeat executive team
    • Bellabeat marketing analytics team: A team of data analysts responsible for collecting, analyzing, and reporting data that helps guide Bellabeat’s marketing strategy. You joined this team six months ago and have been busy learning about Bellabeat’’s mission and business goals — as well as how you, as a junior data analyst, can help Bellabeat achieve them.
  • Products
    • Bellabeat app: The Bellabeat app provides users with health data related to their activity, sleep, stress, menstrual cycle, and mindfulness habits. This data can help users better understand their current habits and make healthy decisions. The Bellabeat app connects to their line of smart wellness products.
    • Leaf: Bellabeat’s classic wellness tracker can be worn as a bracelet, necklace, or clip. The Leaf tracker connects to the Bellabeat app to track activity, sleep, and stress.
    • Time: This wellness watch combines the timeless look of a classic timepiece with smart technology to track user activity, sleep, and stress. The Time watch connects to the Bellabeat app to provide you with insights into your daily wellness.
    • Spring: This is a water bottle that tracks daily water intake using smart technology to ensure that you are appropriately hydrated throughout the day. The Spring bottle connects to the Bellabeat app to track your hydration levels.
    • Bellabeat membership: Bellabeat also offers a subscription-based membership program for users. Membership gives users 24/7 access to fully personalized guidance on nutrition, activity, sleep, health and beauty, and mindfulness based on their lifestyle and goals.

Sršen asks you to analyze smart device usage data in order to gain insight into how consumers use non-Bellabeat smart devices. She then wants you to select one Bellabeat product to apply these insights to in your presentation. These questions will guide your analysis:

    1. What are some trends in smart device usage?
    1. How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?
    1. How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

Index

    1. A clear summary of the business task
    1. A description of all data sources used
    1. Documentation of any cleaning or manipulation of data
    1. A summary of your analysis
    1. Supporting visualizations and key findings
    1. Your top high-level content recommendations based on your analysis

1. Summary of business task

Identify trends in smart devices usage to understand the market needs in order to plan the Bellabeat’s Marketing strategy accordingly.

2. Description of all data sources used

The data used in this analysis is recommended from one of the stakeholders and is the FitBit Fitness Tracker Data set at Kaggle. The data is public domain and is eligible to be copied, modified, and/or distributed without having to ask for the owner’s permission.

Thirty fitbit users agreed on the submission of personal tracker data from a minute-to-minute level of physical activity, heart rate, weight and sleep monitoring. Due to the limited quality and number of responses and the lack of more detailed information such as demographic, socio-cultural as well as income data this could mean a sampling bias but also the date in which this data was gathered which is six years ago it is outdated and therefore could not play a big role in the insights of this analysis.

3. Documentation of any cleaning or manipulation of data

    1. Formatted date columns from certain data sets as they were strings instead of date strings.
    1. Sleep database contained 3 duplicated values, so we created a sleep1 database where only unique IDs were considered.

4. A summary of your analysis

4.1 Quick insights

    1. The mean of lightly active minutes is 1/10 of the sedentary minutes’s mean.
    1. Most people have a sedentary lifestyle.
    1. The majority of people is lightly active, followed by very active and fairy active.
    1. The total steps’ average is 7,638 which is less than the 8,000 daily steps recommended by the CDC research.
    1. The total distance’ average is 5.49 miles.
    1. The average hear rate was 77 beats per minute which lays within the normal 60-100 range.
    1. The average of minutes asleep is 419.2 min which equals 6.99 hours which fairy fall into the 7 to 9 normal or recommended sleep hours for an adult.
    1. Complementary to the sleeping time, the average time an adult spends in bed is 458.5 min or 7.64 hours a day. So from the waking moment to the getting up moment there is about 38.4 minutes.

user_act_type <- average_daily %>% 
  mutate(user_act_type = case_when(mean_daily_steps < 5000 ~ 'Sedentary', 
                                   mean_daily_steps >= 5000 & mean_daily_steps < 7499 ~ 'Lightly Active', 
                                   mean_daily_steps >= 7500 & mean_daily_steps < 9999 ~ 'Fairy Active', 
                                   mean_daily_steps >= 10000 ~ 'Very Active'))
percent_activity_type <- user_act_type %>% 
  group_by(user_act_type) %>% 
  summarize(total = n()) %>%
  mutate(totals = sum(total)) %>%
  group_by(user_act_type) %>%
  summarize(activity_type_percent = total / totals) %>%
  mutate(labels = scales::percent(activity_type_percent))

percent_activity_type$user_act_type <- factor(percent_activity_type$user_act_type, 
                                              levels = c('Sedentary', 'Lightly Active', 'Fairy Active', 'Very Active'))

6. Your top high-level content recommendations based on your analysis

Conclusions and Recommendations

Based on the insights identified in the FitBit Fitness Tracker data, we can assess Bellabeat’s Marketing team and board of directors to define a Marketing strategy to comply with their mission and vision.

    1. To start gathering data from the usage of Bellabeat’s products by asking their users permission to perform further analyzes based on much more reliable data.
    1. Linked to the first recommendation; Bellabeat could decide to include other variables with a powerful impact on the main objective of the analysis such as: age, working flexibily (remote, hybrid, on site) as well as demographic data or a time where cravings are stronger.
    1. As inferred from the pie chart, Sedentary lifestyle is almost 1/4 of the population, Bellabeat could think of activities within the Engineering and Marketing Departments to work together to come up with ideas to motivate people to become more active such as: hackathons.
    1. The Bellabeat App could start showing some notifications or reminders when people have been seated or sedentary for a significant amount of time or when the heart rate starts to raise considerably or just simple random reminders to drink water or take a break and strentch.
    1. The Bellabeat App could start to challenge users within a geographic radius to act as a motive to become more active.
    1. Many people are on a diet to either lose or maintain their weight so, the app could start showing some healthy-tips in moments when anxiety or more cravings are most commonly identified.
